	</div><div class="blogs_entrybody" style="clear:both">
		The weekend arrived with haste.  Scrap and I had maintained a low profile during the past few days using our time to create necessary case file documentation, and to theorize about our current train wreck of a case."Come on Chief, he has to know." Scrap said as he pushed a pile of geek magazines off of a nearby sofa cushion to make room for his monkey behind side. <br/><br/>"Know what?  That he has a bunch of scheming freaks working for him?" I retorted as I cracked open a fresh bottle of Starbucks coffee-flavored Frappuccino.  "Or that his brother is possibly neck deep in doo-doo?" <br/><br/>"That's what I'm saying, man.  Jonathan is 'the man' at this company. Nobody can have their head in the sand that deep." Scrap said with a shake of his long, mop-like hair.  "He called you in to be the bad guy and do all the dirty work.  It's like Miami Vice, boss.  You're Sonny, I'm Tubbs and neither one of dress that well." <br/><br/>I laughed quietly.  Perhaps Scrap was on to something.  <br/><br/>*RING*<br/><br/>"Chief." I said into my cell phone.<br/><br/>"Okay dude, it's Saturday morning.  Are we going in to recover my gear?" Jon said impatiently.  I had a feeling Jon's wife wanted him back home to take care of his "honey do" list.<br/><br/>"You got it.  Meet us down there in an hour?" I asked, motioning Scrap to get our gear ready.<br/><br/>"Check.  I need to leave shortly after lunch." Jon said as he hung up.  <br/><br/>Apparently Jon was under the impression that I was buying him lunch.<br/><br/>"Did you say something about food?" Scrap said as tossed me my laptop bag.<br/><br/>An hour later we arrived at Allison Technologies to find Jon waiting patiently by his sedan.  We marched into the building and approached the storage room where we had left the recording device.  I glanced at the doorframe, carefully inspecting my makeshift tamper detector.<br/><br/>It was intact.<br/><br/>I removed the tamper seal, leaving a mess of sticky tape residue on the door's frame.  Jonathan would understand.<br/><br/>We entered the room, and Jon sat down in front of the recorder.  He opened his notebook and started taking notes on the current date and time.  Jon attached a portable monitor to the recorder and started scrolling through the time lapsed images.  <br/><br/>"There." Jon said as he pointed to the screen and scribbled more notes.  "There's your truck arriving right on time."<br/><br/>The series of events that we then witnessed were exactly as Jose had described.  Tomas and Jeffry assisted Pah in unloading the contents of the truck.  Some boxes were sorted into a smaller pile towards the left of the screen, the rest were sorted into a larger pile on the right and scanned with an inventory gun.  Jeffry moved the boxes on the right side of the screen into a nearby secure storage room.  The boxes on the left side were placed back in the truck.<br/><br/>Jon scrolled through some uninteresting footage until he arrived at Jose in the secure storage room.  Jose performed some arbitrary tasks on his workstation, and then walked to the back of the truck.  He then proceeded to scan the boxes on the truck, and return to the storage room.  For the next ten minutes, Jose worked diligently on his workstation and then appeared to go home.<br/><br/>"How much do you want to bet that if we pull the tag numbers on the boxes in the truck and check their status in the inventory system, they are labeled 'en route'?" I said to Scrap with a wink as I removed my cell phone from its carrying case.<br/><br/>"God I hope you're ordering lunch." Scrap joked.<br/><br/>"Nope, I'm calling Jonathan; and I'm about to give him a real upset stomach." I said.<br/><br/>***<br/><br/>Coming up: The Conclusion!  <p><hr><table width="100%" bgcolor="#FFFFCC" cellpadding="9px">
